# Key Findings

- **Probiotic adjunct significantly increased Bifidobacterium** — from 6.3 to 9.2 lgCFU/g in the probiotic+PPI group versus 6.6 to 8.4 lgCFU/g in PPI-only controls ([[yin-2025-probiotics-ppi-gerd-rct|RCT, n=60]])
- **CRP significantly lower in the probiotic group** (P=0.0486), indicating reduced systemic inflammation beyond what PPI alone achieves
- **Adverse reactions reduced** — 6.6% in the probiotic group versus 16.6% in PPI-only (P<0.01), suggesting probiotics may mitigate PPI side effects
- **[[lactobacillus]] also increased** in the probiotic group, contributing to improved gut microbial balance

# Relevance to WikiBiome

- Provides **RCT-level evidence** (the highest interventional evidence tier) for probiotic benefit in GERD — strengthens the [[bifidobacterium]] and [[lactobacillus]] entity pages
- CRP reduction demonstrates that microbial restoration has measurable anti-inflammatory effects in GERD
- Reduced adverse reactions in the probiotic group supports the safety and tolerability narrative for probiotic interventions

# Relevance to Cureva

- **Primitive 5 (Two-Sided Ecological Engineering)**: This RCT validates the two-sided approach — PPI suppresses acid/inflammation while probiotics restore depleted beneficial taxa (Bifidobacterium, Lactobacillus)
- **Intervention triangle evidence**: Strong I→D edge (RCT showing clinical benefit), strong I→f edge (measurable increase in Bifidobacterium/Lactobacillus), supports probiotic adjunct as a validated intervention for the GERD signature
- The CRP reduction provides an objective biomarker for intervention efficacy beyond symptom scores
- Adverse reaction reduction (6.6% vs 16.6%) strengthens the clinical case for probiotic co-prescription with PPI
